WEBVTT

00:06.528 --> 00:06.702
.

00:06.745 --> 00:08.443
- Previously, on "Colony"...

00:08.486 --> 00:09.531
- We're with an agency called

00:09.574 --> 00:11.141
the Institute for Global
Advancement.

00:11.185 --> 00:13.100
- I don't have enough support
in the camp to stop MacGregor.

00:13.143 --> 00:13.752
- Then you need reinforcements.

00:15.276 --> 00:16.712
- You call a certain
radio frequency

00:17.452 --> 00:19.062
and say a code word.

00:19.106 --> 00:20.281
- Roanoke.

00:20.324 --> 00:21.499
- You are a double agent
travelling

00:21.543 --> 00:23.371
with a known
collaborator.

00:23.414 --> 00:26.243
I thereby sentence you
and your husband to death.

00:34.382 --> 00:35.644
- Gracie!

00:35.687 --> 00:36.645
- Joey, run!

00:38.212 --> 00:40.388
- No! No!

00:43.391 --> 00:44.479
♪

00:45.567 --> 00:47.177
- To the center of the action.

00:47.221 --> 00:48.831
- Switzerland!

00:52.182 --> 00:54.706
- Your responses are being
closely monitored

00:54.750 --> 00:57.753
so it's important that you
answer truthfully.

01:01.626 --> 01:05.630
Who is your favorite
US president?

01:05.674 --> 01:07.806
- I always liked Bill Clinton.

01:07.850 --> 01:10.374
The guy could step in shit
and still smell good.

01:10.418 --> 01:13.551
No one could ever take
that guy down.

01:13.595 --> 01:15.553
- You can have anything
in the world.

01:15.597 --> 01:17.642
What would it be?

01:17.686 --> 01:22.560
- I guess I can't wish
for more wishes?

01:22.604 --> 01:25.389
I guess I always wanted
to drive a Mercedes.

01:25.433 --> 01:29.567
Who is this guy?

01:29.611 --> 01:32.570
- Um...Evan Hazeldine.

01:32.614 --> 01:37.314
He's a state administrator
and law school graduate.

01:38.837 --> 01:41.753
- Um, "The People's College
of Law."

01:43.581 --> 01:45.757
- He failed the Bar
three times.

01:45.801 --> 01:47.759
- You've reached a position
of some power.

01:47.803 --> 01:50.936
Your former fiancée comes
to you

01:50.980 --> 01:52.677
because she's
under investigation,

01:52.721 --> 01:55.202
and wants your help.

01:55.245 --> 01:59.249
- Is this a hypothetical
former fiancée?

01:59.293 --> 02:01.208
- No.

02:08.650 --> 02:11.435
If you lie,
the interview is over.

02:11.479 --> 02:12.828
And your candidacy

02:12.871 --> 02:14.395
with the Institute
for Global Advancement

02:14.438 --> 02:16.266
ends here.

02:22.751 --> 02:26.972
- I wouldn't help her.

02:28.322 --> 02:31.803
- Um, they approved him.

02:33.936 --> 02:36.373
Which grouping is he in?

02:36.417 --> 02:38.288
- Delta 11.

02:47.471 --> 02:48.864
His in-person interview

02:48.907 --> 02:51.345
supported the algorithm's
classification.

02:51.388 --> 02:53.695
- He should be confined
to cubicle somewhere,

02:53.738 --> 02:55.392
not governing a bloc.

02:55.436 --> 02:57.699
You're applying my algorithm
incorrectly.

02:57.742 --> 03:00.310
- Your algorithm's perfect,
Mr. Kynes.

03:00.354 --> 03:01.746
That's why they've partnered
with you.

03:01.790 --> 03:03.270
- The algorithm is meaningless

03:03.313 --> 03:05.837
if you don't apply it
as it was designed.

03:05.881 --> 03:08.231
- The Institute wasn't
interested

03:08.275 --> 03:10.407
in your application method.

03:10.451 --> 03:11.756
What they were interested in

03:11.800 --> 03:13.976
is your algorithm's
uncanny ability

03:14.019 --> 03:17.849
to specifically classify
the human population.

03:17.893 --> 03:20.939
What we do with it
is our business.

03:24.291 --> 03:25.944
Please bring in
the next candidate.

03:25.988 --> 03:32.516
♪

03:32.560 --> 03:35.258
- He's a bureaucrat, Ev.
He's an idiot.

03:35.302 --> 03:38.566
♪

03:38.609 --> 03:39.828
- They're courting disaster

03:39.871 --> 03:41.743
if they keep running things
like this.

03:41.786 --> 03:45.007
- Yeah, well.
What can we do?

03:45.050 --> 03:48.053
♪

03:48.097 --> 03:50.534
- Are you still
up on the network?

03:50.578 --> 03:52.406
How long would it take you
to download it?

03:52.449 --> 03:54.059
- The whole thing.

03:54.103 --> 03:57.019
♪

03:57.062 --> 03:59.543
- Well, now we're talking
7 billion records,

03:59.587 --> 04:00.718
so I have to get up
on a hard line,

04:00.762 --> 04:02.981
but probably 16, 18 hours.

04:03.025 --> 04:05.332
- Could you do it
without being detected?

04:05.375 --> 04:07.508
- Come on.

04:07.551 --> 04:10.075
- I want the whole database
collated and sorted.

04:10.119 --> 04:11.425
- You got it.

04:11.468 --> 04:17.953
♪

04:21.565 --> 04:27.963
♪

05:19.101 --> 05:24.019
- I trust the bath amenities
were to your liking, sir?

05:24.062 --> 05:25.673
- Uh...

05:25.716 --> 05:27.718
Big upgrade
from my previous setup.

05:27.762 --> 05:29.503
- Would you like to see
the rest of the chalet,

05:29.546 --> 05:30.808
or are you hungry?

05:32.506 --> 05:35.509
- I handle all
the household tasks, sir.

05:40.862 --> 05:43.952
- Mm! Mm!

05:54.919 --> 05:56.834
- I've got to warn you, Julien.

05:56.878 --> 05:59.837
It's been a long time
since I've been in love.

06:03.885 --> 06:06.540
I wasn't expecting visitors.

06:06.583 --> 06:11.153
- The car is yours, sir.

06:11.196 --> 06:15.592
- So that means
I can drive it?

06:30.912 --> 06:32.870
- Chief Minister Goldwyn
to see you, sir.

06:32.914 --> 06:35.220
- Helena, I wasn't
expecting you.

06:35.264 --> 06:36.874
- Unannounced drop-in.

06:36.918 --> 06:38.876
I wanted to make sure
that you were relaxing.

06:38.920 --> 06:41.226
Are you happy
with your accommodations?

06:41.270 --> 06:42.880
- A significant understatement.

06:42.924 --> 06:45.622
I have a Julien.

06:45.666 --> 06:47.711
- I figured this
would bore you.

06:47.755 --> 06:52.237
- I could never be bored
being safe, warm, and dry.

06:52.281 --> 06:55.110
- Well, there's plenty of work
for you when you're ready.

06:55.153 --> 06:57.591
- I'm done, Helena.

06:57.634 --> 07:00.463
Everything I could want
is right here.

07:00.507 --> 07:02.552
I'm not going back.

07:03.814 --> 07:06.469
- Good for you.

07:06.513 --> 07:08.906
There is a cocktail party

07:08.950 --> 07:11.692
at the Chancellor's estate
this afternoon.

07:11.735 --> 07:13.737
You should at least get
to know your neighbors.

07:13.781 --> 07:17.045
- I'll have to check
my calendar.

07:17.088 --> 07:18.873
- I'll send a car.

07:18.916 --> 07:20.701
- I already have one.

07:47.162 --> 07:49.599
- She's exhausted, Will.

07:49.643 --> 07:52.776
- We can't stop.

07:52.820 --> 07:58.260
- There was a sign for a town
up the road that way.

07:58.303 --> 08:02.482
Maybe we should check it out.

08:32.860 --> 08:35.210
- It hurts.

08:41.608 --> 08:44.262
Well, changing the bandage
should help.

08:54.055 --> 08:57.188
- I found some water.

09:02.977 --> 09:07.285
- Okay.

09:10.724 --> 09:13.727
- Good.

09:13.770 --> 09:15.293
We should check
the other houses.

09:15.337 --> 09:17.905
See what supplies
we can find.

09:28.872 --> 09:30.613
Come on, damn it.

09:35.226 --> 09:38.316
Come on!

09:39.970 --> 09:42.016
- Because of the way
gasoline's refined.

09:42.059 --> 09:45.628
It breaks down pretty quickly.

09:47.674 --> 09:50.154
- Keep your eye out
for a diesel one.

09:50.198 --> 09:52.287
- Different kind of fuel.

09:52.330 --> 09:57.161
Lasts longer.

09:57.205 --> 09:59.076
We'll find one that works.

09:59.120 --> 10:01.601
We just gotta keep looking,
okay?

10:05.039 --> 10:07.041
Stay here, Grace.

10:07.084 --> 10:11.088
- I found some Neosporin.

10:13.308 --> 10:16.398
- Only recently.
It should still be good.

10:20.184 --> 10:23.318
Yeah, that's good.
Anything else?

10:27.148 --> 10:30.891
- It's empty.

10:33.937 --> 10:40.988
♪

10:56.351 --> 11:00.224
♪

11:00.268 --> 11:02.226
- Mom, Dad.

11:02.270 --> 11:09.320
♪

11:16.371 --> 11:19.679
Maybe that's
where everyone went.

11:22.812 --> 11:26.337
- There'll be cabins
in the Olympic Mountains.

11:26.381 --> 11:29.166
Fresh water,
plenty of fish and game.

11:29.210 --> 11:31.386
Just like Big Bear.

11:33.083 --> 11:35.782
Come on, we gotta use
what daylight we have left.

11:35.825 --> 11:42.876
♪

11:48.751 --> 11:48.882
.

11:52.320 --> 11:58.761
♪

12:13.341 --> 12:15.256
- Alan, I'm glad you made it.

12:15.299 --> 12:20.783
- I might even stay
if they have more of these.

12:22.480 --> 12:24.787
- Everyone, a moment.

12:24.831 --> 12:28.138
I would like to take this time
to introduce you to someone.

12:28.182 --> 12:29.792
Now, you've all heard
the legend

12:29.836 --> 12:32.752
of the insurgent camp
in Region Eight.

12:32.795 --> 12:36.843
Well, the hero behind its
demise is here with us tonight.

12:36.886 --> 12:38.758
Alan Snyder.

12:38.801 --> 12:41.935
I knew that Alan was talented
when I recruited him

12:41.978 --> 12:44.198
to run a bloc
in Los Angeles Colony.

12:44.241 --> 12:45.503
But what I did not know was

12:45.547 --> 12:48.768
that he was also
a gifted double agent.

12:48.811 --> 12:49.856
To Alan.

12:49.899 --> 12:52.728
all: To Alan.

12:52.772 --> 12:56.340
- Enjoy the party.

12:57.864 --> 13:01.171
Once inside, I identified
a rift in the leadership.

13:01.215 --> 13:03.478
Over time, I was able
to exploit it.

13:03.521 --> 13:05.306
And turn them
against each other.

13:07.961 --> 13:11.181
- Enjoy my victory lap.

13:11.225 --> 13:13.314
- You're in a very rare
and enviable position,

13:13.357 --> 13:14.663
but your next choice
is very critical--

13:14.706 --> 13:16.404
- Mr. Snyder.

13:16.447 --> 13:20.277
Sabine Arnaud, Chief Counsel
for the Global Authority.

13:20.321 --> 13:22.410
- Oh, uh, Alan.
A pleasure.

13:22.453 --> 13:25.326
- You've demonstrated your
talent at an opportune time.

13:26.893 --> 13:29.765
- The recent ambush
has left our Hosts reeling.

13:29.809 --> 13:33.551
My group is in a pressing need
for people with your skillset.

13:33.595 --> 13:36.467
I want you to keep me abreast
of your future plans.

13:36.511 --> 13:38.513
- And abreast I shall keep you.

13:38.556 --> 13:44.519
♪

13:45.912 --> 13:47.000
- Sounds like I missed
quite a bit

13:47.043 --> 13:48.523
while I was away.

13:48.566 --> 13:50.351
- Well, we certainly
aren't experiencing

13:50.394 --> 13:52.701
one of the occupation's
better moments.

13:52.744 --> 13:57.619
Which is why there is plenty
of opportunity at play.

13:57.662 --> 13:59.577
The good old boys club
is foundering here.

13:59.621 --> 14:02.711
And the oligarchy is searching
for new, fresh ideas

14:02.754 --> 14:03.973
wherever they can find them.

14:04.017 --> 14:07.542
- I think I'm fresh
out of ideas.

14:07.585 --> 14:09.849
- Hm. Well.

14:09.892 --> 14:11.328
Just think about it.

14:28.868 --> 14:35.875
♪

14:37.441 --> 14:39.879
- Come on over.

14:58.462 --> 15:00.987
- I'm cold.

15:01.030 --> 15:04.991
- All right, extra blanket
is yours, then.

15:08.559 --> 15:09.778
- Car was ditched on the road,

15:09.821 --> 15:11.084
it didn't start,

15:11.127 --> 15:13.521
I thought maybe
we could use this.

15:17.655 --> 15:20.789
I also found a bunch of these.

15:20.832 --> 15:22.443
They were all over the ground.

15:22.486 --> 15:24.880
They must have been air dropped
or something.

15:24.924 --> 15:28.492
It says they've got
medicine, food, shelter,

15:28.536 --> 15:30.712
jobs, everything.

15:30.755 --> 15:32.627
And that they're taking
in anyone who comes.

15:32.670 --> 15:35.717
- Why would a colony be
advertising to take people in?

15:35.760 --> 15:38.111
LA had overcrowding issues
from the go.

15:38.154 --> 15:39.808
- I don't know, Dad.

15:39.851 --> 15:41.549
But it says that it's
a new kind of colony,

15:41.592 --> 15:43.551
and that it's safe there.

15:43.594 --> 15:46.554
- Yeah, I heard
that one before.

15:49.861 --> 15:52.038
- What if they really do have
all these things?

15:52.081 --> 15:56.651
- The Occupation's always had
a good advertising department.

15:56.694 --> 15:58.827
- What's the real plan then,
Dad?

15:58.870 --> 16:00.568
- No colonies!

16:04.528 --> 16:08.010
♪

16:08.054 --> 16:10.795
- Everybody's tired.
We should sleep.

16:10.839 --> 16:12.580
- I'll keep watch.

16:12.623 --> 16:19.674
♪

16:34.080 --> 16:41.391
♪

16:56.102 --> 17:03.413
♪

17:15.425 --> 17:17.993
Wake up! Wake up!

17:18.037 --> 17:20.430
Wake up! Go!
Come on, wake up!

17:20.474 --> 17:21.953
Come on!

17:21.997 --> 17:23.999
Leave it! Leave it!
Come on!

18:22.884 --> 18:24.277
- They're herding us.

18:24.320 --> 18:26.105
♪

18:33.329 --> 18:33.547
.

18:37.725 --> 18:38.465
- Chief Minister Goldwyn, sir.

18:38.508 --> 18:40.510
- Good morning, Helena.

18:40.554 --> 18:42.382
Care to learn about
the fascinating history

18:42.425 --> 18:45.559
of the British Empire?

18:45.602 --> 18:46.995
- What did you think
of the party?

18:47.038 --> 18:48.562
- It was very nice.

18:48.605 --> 18:53.480
But you didn't invite me there
just to show me a good time.

18:53.523 --> 18:55.525
- You've earned a good time.

18:55.569 --> 18:58.615
- Uh-huh.

19:03.142 --> 19:04.969
And?

19:05.013 --> 19:08.059
- The situation may be a little
more dire than I let on.

19:15.458 --> 19:17.721
The labor shortages
that we're facing,

19:17.765 --> 19:20.115
we have never seen
anything like it.

19:20.159 --> 19:23.249
The Hosts had originally
calculated years,

19:23.292 --> 19:24.554
perhaps even a decade

19:24.598 --> 19:27.166
before the enemy fleet
caught up with them.

19:27.209 --> 19:29.646
The estimate has now
dwindled to months.

19:29.690 --> 19:30.778
Maybe less.

19:32.649 --> 19:34.390
- Rendition
the problem colonies

19:34.434 --> 19:36.305
to fix the immediate supply
issues,

19:36.349 --> 19:38.786
and then reboot those colonies.

19:38.829 --> 19:41.049
- The Seattle Protocol.

19:42.572 --> 19:44.270
You can't stay away from this.

19:44.313 --> 19:49.100
- I was just keeping up my side
of the conversation.

19:49.144 --> 19:51.494
- I need to issue
rendition orders

19:51.538 --> 19:53.453
for the Santa Monica
and San Fernando blocs,

19:53.496 --> 19:55.324
but their proxies
are resisting me.

19:57.196 --> 19:58.675
Tell those idiots too bad.

19:58.719 --> 20:00.286
- I need their votes.

20:00.329 --> 20:03.114
Politically,
I've developed a reputation

20:03.158 --> 20:05.726
for being a bit unilateral.

20:05.769 --> 20:07.728
- Tough position.

20:07.771 --> 20:10.209
I hope you can sway them.

20:16.563 --> 20:19.305
That one algorithm
selected everyone

20:19.348 --> 20:21.611
in both the local
and global authorities?

20:21.655 --> 20:24.527
But as extraordinary
as that was,

20:24.571 --> 20:29.837
there was one thing that
Everett Kynes didn't calculate:

20:29.880 --> 20:33.232
Human adaptability.

20:33.275 --> 20:36.191
The world changed radically
after the invasion.

20:36.235 --> 20:41.675
And people had to change
and adapt to meet it.

20:41.718 --> 20:44.286
Some did more than others.

20:44.330 --> 20:48.508
Your ceiling was supposed
to be bloc governor.

20:48.551 --> 20:53.600
But here you are, the toast
of the Global Authority.

20:53.643 --> 20:56.342
You beat the algorithm.

20:56.385 --> 20:59.388
You demonstrated that
you are more than your sum.

21:01.608 --> 21:04.480
It would be a tragic waste
of talent

21:04.524 --> 21:06.700
for you to stop your rise here.

21:06.743 --> 21:13.794
♪

21:20.279 --> 21:21.758
- Uh, I know we met,

21:21.802 --> 21:24.370
but I don't think we were ever
properly introduced.

21:24.413 --> 21:26.197
- Elan.

21:26.241 --> 21:29.549
- And what's your role
in the Global Authority, Elan?

21:29.592 --> 21:31.377
- VGA liaison to the
Transitional Authority

21:31.420 --> 21:32.726
in Region Seven.

21:32.769 --> 21:35.555
Latin America?

21:35.598 --> 21:38.427
- North Africa.

21:38.471 --> 21:40.603
- That must be
interesting work.

21:40.647 --> 21:44.215
- Not as interesting
as your work at the camp.

21:44.259 --> 21:46.174
I'd love to hear about it.

21:46.217 --> 21:51.266
- Well, there's not much to say
that hasn't been said already.

21:51.310 --> 21:52.746
- It must have been satisfying

21:52.789 --> 21:54.530
not only to see
those terrorists

21:54.574 --> 21:56.750
reap their punishment,

21:56.793 --> 22:00.536
but to know that you had
a direct hand in it.

22:00.580 --> 22:03.713
- It was very violent.

22:03.757 --> 22:06.760
- Tell me about it.

22:12.679 --> 22:15.246
- Any details you're willing
to share.

22:18.293 --> 22:20.513
♪

22:27.650 --> 22:30.566
- Hang in there, Gracie.

22:42.448 --> 22:43.753
- I think she's going septic.

22:43.797 --> 22:45.407
- We have to take her
to Seattle.

22:45.451 --> 22:46.626
- No!

22:46.669 --> 22:50.325
- She'll die too, if we don't.

22:50.369 --> 22:52.327
- If we walk in there,
that's it for you and me.

22:52.371 --> 22:54.198
They'll ID us and arrest us.

22:54.242 --> 22:55.548
- I don't care.

22:55.591 --> 22:58.638
I don't care!

23:05.296 --> 23:11.912
- You have to be okay
with this too.

23:11.955 --> 23:14.915
- Maybe they won't know
who you are...

23:14.958 --> 23:18.875
Or maybe we can change
our names again.

23:18.919 --> 23:21.269
- No.

23:21.312 --> 23:23.880
We can't go into this on hope.

23:26.579 --> 23:30.234
- I know.

24:06.445 --> 24:08.359
- Of course not, sir.

24:08.403 --> 24:12.581
- Any chance you could wrangle
an IGA incident report for me?

24:41.610 --> 24:48.661
♪

25:02.979 --> 25:10.334
♪

25:14.817 --> 25:17.472
♪

25:17.516 --> 25:18.778
This is Alan Snyder.

25:18.821 --> 25:22.477
I need to speak
with Helena Goldwyn.

25:22.521 --> 25:24.392
Wake her up.

25:27.569 --> 25:27.743
.

25:54.727 --> 25:56.293
- Hey, I'm Will.

25:56.337 --> 25:57.947
- Uh, Jim.

25:59.732 --> 26:01.168
- Seattle.

26:01.211 --> 26:02.604
- Us too.

26:02.648 --> 26:05.128
Our daughter's very sick.

26:06.869 --> 26:08.044
- Broken arm.

26:08.088 --> 26:09.959
It's infected.

26:10.003 --> 26:15.008
She's not gonna make it
if we go on foot.

26:15.051 --> 26:18.098
- I mean, you can see
we don't have room.

26:25.192 --> 26:27.673
- I'm at the end of my rope,
Jim.

26:42.905 --> 26:45.560
- Tell you what.

26:45.604 --> 26:47.606
Let me drop them off,
I'll come back for you.

26:47.649 --> 26:48.998
I won't be half a day.

26:49.042 --> 26:51.218
- She might not have
that kind of time.

26:59.008 --> 27:01.881
- We can take her.

27:01.924 --> 27:04.013
They're supposed to have great
medical care in Seattle.

27:04.057 --> 27:08.322
We could have her there
in a couple of hours.

27:10.280 --> 27:13.022
- Let my wife come with you.

27:13.066 --> 27:15.982
- There's not room for that.

27:18.724 --> 27:21.335
- Your oldest,
she can stay with us.

27:21.378 --> 27:22.815
We'll take good care of her.

27:22.858 --> 27:25.861
- I--
- We're not bargaining here.

27:25.905 --> 27:29.299
We're sorry about your
daughter, we really are.

27:29.343 --> 27:32.215
And you're welcome to take
our generous offer.

27:32.259 --> 27:35.262
Otherwise, we need to move on.

27:38.961 --> 27:40.876
- We need the car.

27:43.662 --> 27:45.272
You can take all your supplies.

27:45.315 --> 27:47.404
We'll leave the car for you
outside the city.

27:47.448 --> 27:51.844
♪

27:51.887 --> 27:53.367
- You know I can't do that.

27:53.410 --> 27:55.935
- But she's gonna die
if we don't.

27:55.978 --> 27:57.719
♪

27:57.763 --> 27:59.068
- Jim, drive.

27:59.112 --> 28:01.027
- Okay--
- Drive the goddamn car!

28:04.073 --> 28:07.381
♪

28:07.424 --> 28:09.775
- Get out, all of you.

28:09.818 --> 28:11.994
♪

28:12.038 --> 28:14.257
- All right, do what he says.

28:14.301 --> 28:15.389
Do what he says!

28:15.432 --> 28:16.956
- I told you not to stop!

28:16.999 --> 28:20.742
♪

28:20.786 --> 28:22.091
- Take what you want.

28:22.135 --> 28:24.354
♪

28:24.398 --> 28:26.705
- All right.

28:26.748 --> 28:27.967
♪

28:28.010 --> 28:30.099
- Get Gracie in the back.

28:30.143 --> 28:37.193
♪

28:47.377 --> 28:49.858
- I'm sorry.

28:49.902 --> 28:56.952
♪

29:06.745 --> 29:09.965
- Proxies, welcome to Davos!
May I?

29:10.009 --> 29:12.272
Table for three?
I brought wine.

29:12.315 --> 29:15.405
- Well, I'm so glad to see
you're alive and well.

29:15.449 --> 29:18.887
- Come on, Tony, you're a
better liar than that. Cheers!

29:18.931 --> 29:20.802
- Hey, congratulations
on your success

29:20.846 --> 29:22.238
at the Resistance camp.

29:22.282 --> 29:24.197
- We live in a time
of unlikely heroes.

29:24.240 --> 29:26.982
Speaking of which,
I have brought the both of you

29:27.026 --> 29:29.942
an opportunity to cover
yourselves in glory.

29:31.421 --> 29:33.989
- Give the Chief Minister
the vote she needs,

29:34.033 --> 29:37.863
and surrender your blocs
for total rendition.

29:41.040 --> 29:44.826
- I see the IGA's hero is
still carrying Helena's water.

29:44.870 --> 29:47.176
- You would keep your fife
following the rendition.

29:47.220 --> 29:49.396
You would just inherit
new subjects.

29:49.439 --> 29:51.006
- Along with a view of
that new factory

29:51.050 --> 29:52.051
they want to build downtown.

29:52.094 --> 29:53.835
- You want a factory

29:53.879 --> 29:55.489
as close to your colony
as you can get it,

29:55.532 --> 29:57.534
because those are
the only sites the RAPs

29:57.578 --> 29:59.406
will be protecting
when their enemies do show up.

29:59.449 --> 30:01.147
- It also makes us a target.

30:01.190 --> 30:03.540
- It's a double-edged sword,
to be sure.

30:03.584 --> 30:05.499
- I've got everything I need
in Santa Monica.

30:05.542 --> 30:07.370
And no snow.

30:09.068 --> 30:12.506
I always took you
for the smart one.

30:12.549 --> 30:14.856
- If they need
to staunch the labor shortage,

30:14.900 --> 30:17.859
then I'll discuss
the rendition order.

30:17.903 --> 30:19.556
But Helena has to find
another location

30:19.600 --> 30:22.255
in Region Eight
for her factory.

30:22.298 --> 30:24.213
- I feel compelled to admit

30:24.257 --> 30:26.476
I haven't been entirely
truthful with you.

30:26.520 --> 30:28.130
Waiter?

30:28.174 --> 30:31.351
You see, this meeting
wasn't a negotiation.

30:31.394 --> 30:34.093
It was
a professional courtesy.

30:34.136 --> 30:36.399
Can you please invite
my friends to join us?

30:39.359 --> 30:46.409
♪

30:48.455 --> 30:50.413
These are the two gentlemen
who need to be questioned.

30:50.457 --> 30:52.894
Questioned about what?

30:52.938 --> 30:55.549
- I spent a long time embedded
with the Resistance,

30:55.592 --> 30:57.116
talked to a lot of people.

30:57.159 --> 31:00.119
I was very surprised
to learn how both of you

31:00.162 --> 31:02.338
had been so sympathetic
to their cause!

31:02.382 --> 31:05.167
- Yes, Proxies Lee and Fleming,

31:05.211 --> 31:06.908
I took detailed notes.

31:06.952 --> 31:11.565
♪

31:11.608 --> 31:13.306
I didn't want to do this,

31:13.349 --> 31:16.091
not to two former colleagues,
but I had no choice.

31:16.135 --> 31:19.094
I gave a full briefing
to the Security Directorate.

31:19.138 --> 31:22.097
- This is bullshit!
This is a setup!

31:22.141 --> 31:24.273
♪

31:24.317 --> 31:29.583
- Unfortunately, treason
is a hard stink to get rid of.

31:29.626 --> 31:31.454
Especially here.

31:31.498 --> 31:38.548
♪

32:09.884 --> 32:12.887
- How we doing,
Gracie

32:17.500 --> 32:19.502
Where are we?

32:19.546 --> 32:20.982
- We're close,
but we're gonna have to walk

32:21.026 --> 32:22.288
the rest of the way.

32:25.030 --> 32:27.336
- I got you.

32:27.380 --> 32:34.387
♪

32:46.573 --> 32:53.928
♪

33:08.595 --> 33:14.253
♪

33:35.404 --> 33:35.578
.

33:38.973 --> 33:42.759
♪

33:42.803 --> 33:44.457
- Hey, help!
I need your help!

33:44.500 --> 33:46.763
Please, my sister's
very badly hurt.

33:48.461 --> 33:51.072
- Broken arm. We reset it,
but it's infected.

33:51.116 --> 33:53.335
- I need a rapid response team
at the Eastern ingress.

33:53.379 --> 33:55.337
How old is she?
- She's 11. Her name is Grace.

33:55.381 --> 33:57.339
- Okay, help is coming.

33:57.383 --> 33:59.341
Grace is 11 years old.
She has a broken left arm,

33:59.385 --> 34:00.821
and might be septic!

34:00.864 --> 34:02.779
♪

34:02.823 --> 34:05.391
- Okay, baby.

34:06.653 --> 34:09.090
- Careful, careful, careful!

34:12.789 --> 34:14.791
- Hang in there, baby.

34:14.835 --> 34:16.532
Hang in there.
We're here.

34:16.576 --> 34:18.534
We're here.
You're safe.

34:18.578 --> 34:21.102
- Hey, they need to take her
to the medical tent, okay?

34:21.146 --> 34:22.364
♪

34:22.408 --> 34:24.714
- Let them take her.
- Okay.

34:24.758 --> 34:27.326
♪

34:27.369 --> 34:30.155
- You can see Grace
after they stabilize her, okay?

34:30.198 --> 34:32.592
Okay? Come with me.

34:34.376 --> 34:41.470
♪

34:57.443 --> 34:59.706
- I'm Iris, your advocate.

34:59.749 --> 35:02.752
I'm going to see that you are
placed in a home that offers

35:02.796 --> 35:04.580
the best fit for your family.

35:04.624 --> 35:06.234
Okay?

35:06.278 --> 35:08.671
Can we start with your names?

35:08.715 --> 35:11.413
- Dalton.

35:11.457 --> 35:14.634
James, Laura, and Sean.

35:14.677 --> 35:17.593
- Okay,
and let's not forget Grace.

35:17.637 --> 35:20.814
And where are the Daltons from?

35:20.857 --> 35:23.338
- Riverside, California.

35:26.211 --> 35:30.432
- Now, I just need to snap
some photos of you.

35:30.476 --> 35:34.567
We'll get beauty shots later.

35:38.571 --> 35:40.181
All right.

35:40.225 --> 35:43.315
So this is your intake tent,
number 306.

35:43.358 --> 35:45.186
One of you should be here
at all times,

35:45.230 --> 35:46.448
in case we need
to speak with you

35:46.492 --> 35:47.623
or update you.

35:47.667 --> 35:49.190
The camp is pretty well-marked,

35:49.234 --> 35:50.583
so you can find your way
to wash facilities

35:50.626 --> 35:52.367
and ration stations.

35:52.411 --> 35:54.282
- And how do we get
updates on Gracie?

35:54.326 --> 35:57.590
- They know to come to me
as soon as there's news.

35:57.633 --> 35:59.548
She's in really good hands.

35:59.592 --> 36:01.333
- Thank you.

36:01.376 --> 36:03.204
- In the meantime, I'm gonna
get your case opened,

36:03.248 --> 36:05.293
so we can start processing you.

36:05.337 --> 36:12.344
♪

36:18.480 --> 36:21.222
- Why don't you, um--

36:21.266 --> 36:23.833
Why don't you go see if you can
find us some food

36:23.877 --> 36:25.400
and maybe a change of clothes,

36:25.444 --> 36:27.576
and we'll wait here
for news on Gracie.

36:28.751 --> 36:30.449
- Okay.

36:30.492 --> 36:37.543
♪

36:51.905 --> 36:59.217
♪

37:07.747 --> 37:10.445
- Clusters C and D
are now departing

37:10.489 --> 37:12.012
through the South Gate.

37:12.055 --> 37:14.406
If you've received
your transfer papers,

37:14.449 --> 37:17.844
please report there now.

37:29.638 --> 37:32.641
- They have tons
of food and water.

37:32.685 --> 37:36.384
Places we can clean up
and change too.

37:36.428 --> 37:39.779
I saw the administration tents.

37:39.822 --> 37:42.390
They have computers and cameras

37:42.434 --> 37:45.350
and everything.

37:49.919 --> 37:52.400
This place is wired.

37:52.444 --> 37:56.448
And they could easily find out
who we really are.

37:56.491 --> 38:00.321
- There's a good chance
they already know.

38:00.365 --> 38:02.062
- If they come for us,

38:02.105 --> 38:05.283
you have to look
after your sister.

38:09.852 --> 38:12.594
- I can't--I don't want to.

38:15.554 --> 38:17.556
- None of us want any of this.

38:17.599 --> 38:24.519
♪

38:24.563 --> 38:26.565
- You two are all we have left.

38:26.608 --> 38:29.872
♪

38:29.916 --> 38:31.787
Promise us you'll do this.

38:31.831 --> 38:38.838
♪

38:42.407 --> 38:44.452
- I'll take care of her.

38:44.496 --> 38:51.372
♪

39:01.208 --> 39:01.382
.

39:01.426 --> 39:03.819
- I did.

39:05.168 --> 39:05.343
- You said that you were taking
them to dinner.

39:06.169 --> 39:06.822
- It needed to be public.

39:07.867 --> 39:09.172
- Lee and Fleming
have an alliance.

39:09.216 --> 39:10.957
They have friends all
over the IGA.

39:11.000 --> 39:15.091
Which is why I was
in this particular situation.

39:15.135 --> 39:17.790
- Who's going to dare to back
a couple of bloc governors

39:17.833 --> 39:19.313
who were just accused
of treason

39:19.357 --> 39:21.968
by the IGA's golden boy?

39:23.796 --> 39:26.189
- I've worked with them
a long time, Alan.

39:26.233 --> 39:28.322
- Well, you don't anymore.

39:31.369 --> 39:32.370
♪

39:32.413 --> 39:34.720
At this level of the game,

39:34.763 --> 39:37.287
you need a fixer
with a mailed fist,

39:37.331 --> 39:39.812
not a velvet glove.

39:39.855 --> 39:41.683
- I thought you'd retired.

39:41.727 --> 39:43.729
- I decided I didn't want
to sit around,

39:43.772 --> 39:46.993
listening to the voices in my
head for the rest of my life.

39:47.036 --> 39:54.087
♪

39:57.133 --> 39:58.961
- It's good news.

39:59.005 --> 40:00.310
Grace has been stabilized.

40:00.354 --> 40:01.921
She has a really bad infection,

40:01.964 --> 40:04.097
but she should recover
just fine.

40:06.012 --> 40:09.015
- Thank God!

40:10.146 --> 40:12.758
- I need you to come
with me now, Mr. Dalton.

40:17.893 --> 40:19.721
- For an interview.

40:19.765 --> 40:26.815
♪

40:41.395 --> 40:48.707
♪

40:54.843 --> 40:56.279
Have a seat.

40:56.323 --> 41:03.373
♪

41:08.988 --> 41:11.033
Your name, for the record?

41:11.077 --> 41:15.081
- James Dalton.

41:15.124 --> 41:18.084
- Why did you come to Seattle,
Mr. Dalton?

41:18.127 --> 41:21.870
♪

41:21.914 --> 41:22.871
- Asylum.

41:22.915 --> 41:25.221
- Don't be nervous.

41:25.265 --> 41:27.963
I know you've been
through a lot.

41:28.007 --> 41:30.270
We're just
establishing a profile,

41:30.313 --> 41:32.228
so that we can find
the best placement

41:32.272 --> 41:34.361
for you and your family.

41:34.404 --> 41:36.363
♪

41:36.406 --> 41:37.843
Need some water?

41:37.886 --> 41:40.410
♪

41:40.454 --> 41:42.804
Did you have a job
before the Arrival?

41:42.848 --> 41:44.458
♪

41:44.502 --> 41:47.243
- Yeah.

41:47.287 --> 41:48.897
- Auto mechanic.

41:48.941 --> 41:51.421
A little bit of construction.

41:51.465 --> 41:55.338
I'm good with my hands.

41:55.382 --> 41:57.515
- I'd like to run you
through something

41:57.558 --> 41:59.908
that's kind of like an IQ test,

41:59.952 --> 42:02.302
if that's okay with you,
Mr. Dalton.

42:02.345 --> 42:06.959
♪

42:07.002 --> 42:08.917
- Okay.

42:08.961 --> 42:11.006
- As you can see,
you're being filmed,

42:11.050 --> 42:14.357
and all of your answers
are being monitored,

42:14.401 --> 42:17.970
so it's important
that you answer truthfully.
